This holder is designed to work with the short pencils you can get from IKEA (and other places), but it should work for any "shorter" tool with a diameter of around 7 mm (1/4 inch or a little more).

title: Low profile ducted fan for Mendel90 with E3Dv4 hot end

description.text:
When I bought a new hot end from E3D-online I discovered that it wouldn't fit inside the fan duct on my Mendel90, so I redesigned it.
This duct is for a 60 mm fan and has a larger central hole and a slimmer profile, which allows it to sit underneath the nozzle cooling fan.
This version was created in Cubify Invent and is made available as a .FUN file as well as an STL file.

You want the duct to be nice and air tight so don't scrimp on the plastic. You should probably stick to using ABS because of its proximity to the hot end.
I printed mine at 0.3 mm layer height, 0.49 mm width, 50% infill and 100 mm/s speed.
The fan is held in place with four small self-tapping screws.
The duct was attached to the same brackets as I used in the original design (see the 'Derived from' link). These are quite easy to modify in any basic CAD package.

description.text: After playing with both the Heart Gears http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:6291 and Gear Gears http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:6533, a good friend wanted something different. She liked the way the Heart Gears moved and is totally into solar power, so she asked if I could make gears that looked like a sun. Believe it or not, I am very new at this and had very little experience with OpenSCAD. I understood that if I could get an stl file of a sun it should be relatively straightforward. Unfortunately, I could not find a good one. However, I did find the Geek Campfire thing by jonschwartz http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:578, and thought it would look pretty cool if I put several of them around a squashed sphere. Voila! I made her one in translucent blue PLA (at her request) and now you can make one too. The image of the one I printed is an earlier revision (hence the flat ends of the two tallest gears), but I fixed that in this release. I have included an stl of the complete assembly, but only so you can see what it looks like.

Print one of each gear and one core. Attach the gears to the core with M3 screws (I used 18mm long ones) I included a couple of files with four gears on one plate if you have enough build area. I printed these with .35mm layers with one extra shell with reasonable results. If you want to play with this in OpenSCAD, you will need to get the parametric involute gear v5.0 OpenSCAD file from http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:3575 and the Geek Campfire stl file from http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:578. Put both of these files in the same directory with sun_gears.stl and have fun (but don't get burned).

I updated the files to subtract the nozzle diameter, making for a snug fit (the original proved loose in testing) and also changed some of the parameters for a less tapered Wyrm (more Wyrmy I suppose).

I can imagine a whole host of new printer accessories with style and theme rather than just functionality, maybe you will make one soon?

Les

Print it, clean it up, slide it on, feed filament through space between Wyrms or raise filement above Wyrm tails and twist Wyrms as filament lowers into position.

comments.text: l am new to 3D printing, about how long does it take to print an object with this detail?
comments.author: jhspriggs

comments.text: That depends on a lot of different factors that we don't know. Each printing technology (sla, sls, fdm, etc.) is going to have different levels of detail that they are capable of to begin with, and will have their own challenges with respect to support, and such. As it is set up, this appears to be optimized for fdm, That said, even here there are many factors that affect print speed. As an example for this level of detail, I'd like to print with a finer nozzle, say, .2mm rather than the .5 that I have, and print at layer heights of .1 rather than the default of .2. Each of those factors will result in different times taken for a given print head speed. So if I can print at 50 mm/s, printing .1mm layers instead of .2mm will double the time it takes to print. To use a .2mm nozzle instead of a .5mm nozzle I'm looking at about 2.5 times as long. If I do both, I'm looking at about 5 times as long, so if I could print this in 8 hours at .5mm nozzle and .2 mm layers (which would show layers like crazy) it would take at least 40 hours to print this at a higher resolution.

The UBQ 180/200 is a 3d printed unibody quadcopter. Main intention was to have a frame that's fast to replace and fairly light. You should be able to move to the new frame after unscrewing a few things and cutting a few zip ties. It takes about 10-15min to swap the electronics and motors to a new frame.

Flight testing showed that it is very sturdy, especially for a printed frame.

It holds common FCs and most ESCs. Even large ESCs like 20A Afros will fit, but it's gonna be a tight fit. Motor mounting pattern should fit almost any motor from 1306 to 22XX. Also standard FPV equipment fits in.

UBQ 180 - 4" props
UBQ 200 - 4 or 5" props

You'll need:

4-8 standoffs 35mm (skip them or use shorter ones if you don't plan to use the camera mount)
4-8 m3x12 metal screws

Made a mold for dropshot jiggs to use with my syringe for soft plastics such as plastisol etc!
The syringe can be found among all my other uploads!
Or by clicking here: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:909519

To hold the mold together whilst using it just use some strong rubber bands, or a vice if you have one.
But be sure to not tighten the vice to hard so the plastic might break!
After making a lure just use a scissor and remove the unwanted features left after moulding.
And be sure to lube the mold before with some sort of release agent, ordinary cooking oil works just fine!

comments.text: Do you have any issues with the hot plastisol melting the form?  Or are you recasting in plaster or something?
comments.author: thegreathoe

comments.text:
No I haven't had any problems, I just use quite thick shelling and abs plastic and acetone the inside of where the plastisol is supposed to go to get it smooth and flowing through it good.
This also makes the lure have a better shinier finish!
One trick is to put it in the fridge/freezer after you filled the form.
Be sure to press until the plastisol comes out the small hole on the side to know its filled properly.
You can also make the exits of the form where the paddles meet the outrunners a bit wider, I noticed mine became a bit "squished" and a little bit to narrow.
Easy fix with some fine pointy files :)!

I have designed a catamaran which is big enough to carry humans (two swimmer each swimmer has a volume of 60l so it should carry 120kg). You can just float down a river or make some unique extensions on it. Design it as a sailing catamaran (with mast and sail) or as a pedal-boat with a pedal drive (3D-printable gears, drive chain, …). Just imagine what you could make with it.

The printable parts are mainly for the swimmer. The swimmers are out of several 150mm high segments (Height should fit exactly for Makerbot Replicator 5.Gen). The segments for the swimmer must be put together. After this you need to glue them waterproof. The best would be some fiberglass mat which is glued with epoxy resin on the joints of the swimmer.
The platform is made out of wood, because I found no solution to make it strong and 3D-printable in this size.

I was just able to print a model at 10% of the original size because I have no printer witch can print such huge parts, but every Makerbot or other printer should be able to print. The model floated very well.

I would be very happy to see the catamaran float. So if you have the opportunities to print it try it please. But be careful at the first tests. If the swimmers are breaking you could drown.

Have fun with it.

title: Not so ugly Mr Door Stopper

description.text: I was impressed with Roland's Mr Door Stopper and intended to print one as soon as I got my printer.  Of course that plan got derailed by everything else I saw on Thingiverse!  Then I came across TheronRogers' ingenious idea of hanging the door stopper on the door handle when not in use... and so was born the Not so ugly Mr Door Stopper.

My first version just used a single shell with only 3% infil and 0.27mm layers so I could check the dimensions.  It took a bit less than 2 hrs to print and seems strong enough for the job - but I probably will bump the infil up to 5% for any future ones I print, and maybe double shells just to be sure.   
I also use the shiny side up as the slightly rougher surface gives good grip on carpet - and reasonable on tiles.  
Also, make sure you hang it on the side of the door away from the jamb... I was going to try and fiddle with the centre of gravity or length of arms to stop it encroaching on the jamb zone, but got a bit lazy when I realised I could just hang it on the other side ;-)

comments.text: Great design.  I am printing them up for the custodians in our school and they love it!

Managing the wires

• Simply attach it on the rods of your RepRap by pushing the opened end against the bar until it locks.

  • Either push the wires through the large loop, or push them through the tight opening of the loop.
    If you have a clear idea of which wires should go through one clam, I'd recommend you should insert them before attaching the clam to the frame, especially in crowded places.

  • If you want to remove wires, of remove the clam entirely, just replace push by... pull ;)

This is a set of clams to support the Minitronics controller board produced by RepRapWorld, together with its accompanying fan.
The authors of the board have also designed a thingy to attach the fan to the board http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:85977, but well, it was not what I was looking for. This design will allow you to independently attach the Minitronics board and the cooling fan to the rods of your RepRap, provided the frame is made of 6 mm rods.

• Print 2 miniclams and 1 fanclam.
  • Have at hand 7 bolts M3x12 and 7 M3 nuts.
  • Attach the miniclams to the 2 holes at the end of one long edge of the board, using couple of nut&bolt pairs.
    I would recommend the edge with the stepper connectors, but this is up to you.
    Make sure that when tightening the crews you left aside of the plastic piece any soldered terminal.
  • Position the clams along the rod in the desired position and gently push the ensemble against the bar, until the clams will fully attach to the rod.
  • Secure with a couple of nut&bolt pairs.
  • Attach the fan to the bracket of the fanclam using with a couple of nut&bolt pairs.
  • Position the clam on the rod, somewhere between the 2 miniclams, and push it to attach to the bar, then secure with a nut&bolt pair.

description.text: This is a simple drill or spindle mount which fits onto a standard Prusa X carriage in place of an extruder/hotend (I use . It is made for tools that have a standard 43mm mounting neck.  I use an old Minicraft MB510 mini drill (9-18V, 60W, 20000rpm), but since the 43mm collar is quite standard, I assume that the mount will fit many other tools as well (eg. from Proxxon or Dremel). Just make sure that your tool is not too heavy and that mount and x-carriage do not occlude any ventilation holes of your particular tool.
